  "prompt": "What are some efficient algorithms to compute nCr in Java?",
  "response": "Here are several efficient algorithms to compute nCr (combinations) in Java, along with their time and space complexities:\n\n1. Basic Factorial Method (Least Efficient):\n```java\npublic static long combinationsBasic(int n, int r) {\n    return factorial(n) / (factorial(r) * factorial(n - r));\n}\n\nprivate static long factorial(int num) {\n    if (num <= 1) return 1;\n    long result = 1;\n    for (int i = 2; i <= num; i++) {\n        result *= i;\n    }\n    return result;\n}\n```\n- Time Complexity: O(n)\n- Space Complexity: O(1)\n- Drawback: Prone to integer overflow for large numbers\n\n2. Dynamic Programming Approach:\n```java\npublic static long combinationsDynamic(int n, int r) {\n    // Optimize by taking min(r, n-r)\n    r = Math.min(r, n - r);\n    \n    // Create DP table\n    long[][] dp = new long[n + 1][r + 1];\n    \n    // Fill base cases\n    for (int i = 0; i <= n; i++) {\n        dp[i][0] = 1;\n    }\n    \n    // Compute combinations\n    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {\n        for (int j = 1; j <= Math.min(i, r); j++) {\n            dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + dp[i-1][j];\n        }\n    }\n    \n    return dp[n][r];\n}\n```\n- Time Complexity: O(n*r)\n- Space Complexity: O(n*r)\n- Advantages: Handles intermediate calculations without overflow\n- Good for multiple queries\n\n3. Space-Optimized Dynamic Programming:\n```java\npublic static long combinationsSpaceOptimized(int n, int r) {\n    r = Math.min(r, n - r);\n    \n    // Use 1D array instead of 2D\n    long[] dp = new long[r + 1];\n    dp[0] = 1;\n    \n    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {\n        for (int j = Math.min(i, r); j > 0; j--) {\n            dp[j] += dp[j-1];\n        }\n    }\n    \n    return dp[r];\n}\n```\n- Time Complexity: O(n*r)\n- Space Complexity: O(r)\n- More memory-efficient\n\n4. Multiplicative Formula (Most Efficient for Large n, Small r):\n```java\npublic static long combinationsMultiplicative(int n, int r) {\n    // Ensure r is not larger than n-r for efficiency\n    r = Math.min(r, n - r);\n    \n    // Use long to prevent overflow\n    long result = 1;\n    \n    // Compute nCr using multiplicative formula\n    for (int i = 1; i <= r; i++) {\n        result *= (n - i + 1);\n        result /= i;\n    }\n    \n    return result;\n}\n```\n- Time Complexity: O(r)\n- Space Complexity: O(1)\n- Best for small r\n- Minimizes intermediate calculations\n\n5. Modular Combinations (For competitive programming):\n```java\npublic static long combinationsModular(int n, int r, int mod) {\n    // Handle base cases\n    if (r > n) return 0;\n    if (r > n/2) r = n - r;\n    \n    long result = 1;\n    for (int i = 1; i <= r; i++) {\n        result = (result * (n - i + 1) / i) % mod;\n    }\n    \n    return result;\n}\n```\n- Time Complexity: O(r)\n- Space Complexity: O(1)\n- Handles large numbers with modular arithmetic\n\nComparative Notes:\n- Use Multiplicative Formula for small r\n- Use Dynamic Programming for multiple queries\n- Use Modular version for competitive programming problems\n- Always be cautious of integer overflow\n\nExample Usage:\n```java\npublic static void main(String[] args) {\n    int n = 10, r = 3;\n    System.out.println(\"10C3 (Basic): \" + combinationsBasic(n, r));\n    System.out.println(\"10C3 (Dynamic): \" + combinationsDynamic(n, r));\n    System.out.println(\"10C3 (Space Optimized): \" + combinationsSpaceOptimized(n, r));\n    System.out.println(\"10C3 (Multiplicative): \" + combinationsMultiplicative(n, r));\n    System.out.println(\"10C3 (Modular): \" + combinationsModular(n, r, 1_000_000_007));\n}\n```\n\nChoose the algorithm based on your specific use case, considering factors like:\n- Size of inputs\n- Number of queries\n- Memory constraints\n- Potential for overflow",
